# Getting Started with Docker

Docker is a platform for building, shipping, and running applications in containers. This tutorial will walk you through the basics.

## Prerequisites

- [ ] Install Docker Desktop
- [ ] Verify installation with `docker --version`
- [ ] Create a Docker Hub account

## Your First Container

```bash
docker run hello-world
```

This pulls the `hello-world` image and runs it in a container. You should see a confirmation message.

## Writing a Dockerfile

Create a file named `Dockerfile` in your project:

```dockerfile
FROM node:20-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
COPY . .
EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["node", "server.js"]
```

## Building and Running

```bash
# Build the image
docker build -t my-app .

# Run the container
docker run -p 3000:3000 my-app
```

## Docker Compose

For multi-container applications, use Docker Compose:

```yaml
services:
  web:
    build: .
    ports:
      - "3000:3000"
  db:
    image: postgres:16
    environment:
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: secret
```

Then run:

```bash
docker compose up
```

## Common Commands

| Command | Description |
| --- | --- |
| `docker ps` | List running containers |
| `docker images` | List local images |
| `docker stop <id>` | Stop a container |
| `docker rm <id>` | Remove a container |
| `docker logs <id>` | View container logs |

W> Never store secrets in Docker images. Use environment variables or secret management tools.

N> Docker Desktop includes Docker Compose by default since version 4.0.

